  "opinion": "As a 25-year-old woman living in Bari, Italy, working as a plumber with only an upper secondary education, I've witnessed firsthand how the gender gap in science isn't just a statistic—it's a lived reality. When I tried to get into a technical workshop last year, the instructors were overwhelmingly male, and they didn't even acknowledge my questions about fluid dynamics. This isn't unique to me; it's a pattern I've noticed in my community. The gap isn't just about who's in the lab—it's about who gets to be seen as capable. My parents, one with upper secondary education and the other with lower secondary, taught me to value practical skills over theoretical ones, but even that has been shaped by societal expectations. I'm depressed a lot, and the lack of role models in science that look like me makes it harder to believe I could ever contribute. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. We need to start in schools, not with lectures about 'diversity,' but with hands-on projects that show science as a tool for everyday problems—like fixing a leaky pipe or understanding how water flows through a city. It's not about changing the system overnight; it's about creating spaces where people from all backgrounds feel they belong. My depression makes me anxious about this, but I know that if we don't act now, fewer women will see themselves in the scientific field. We need to listen to those who are already there, like my friends who work in construction or engineering, and build bridges instead of walls. The answer isn't just policy—it's about making science feel relevant and accessible to everyone, especially those who've been told they don't belong.",
